Something clicked in Kiev. This was more like the effective Chelsea from the latter stages of last season, when attacking threat was allied to the required work-rate and defensive nous. The likes of Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic, so off-colour up to now, reacted to’s recent criticisms and were recognisable against Dynamo as the talents of last term, with each conjuring their most convincing displays of the campaign to date. Here was evidence methods are sparking a response, with the last four days having now yielded successive clean sheets for the first time since mid-April. Porto top Champions League Group G after victory over Maccabi Tel Aviv Read more The teams destiny in Group G remains in their own hands, and there will be confidence the remaining home fixtures can be won, together with the trip to the whipping boys Maccabi Tel Aviv, to smooth passage into the knockout phase. The sense of satisfaction obtained here, though, should maintain the optimism generated fros welcome win over Aston Villa. said Mourinho. We are recovering some of that compactness, solidarity, effort, tactical discipline, qualities which are very important when you are not flying or playing with that confidence or flair, when your attacking players are not killing [opponents]. So in three days, two solid performances are good for us There was, inevitably, one gripe that needed to be aired. The game had edged just beyond the quarter-hour mark when Cesc Fàbregas wriggled into the penalty area and was clipped by Serhiy Rybalka, only for the Slovenian official, Damir Skomina, to wave away the appeals for a spot-kick.
